38:17.343 --> 38:24.109
Well, Corbus was here a couple years ago and tried to negotiate with our Princeton Photographs Division.

38:24.169 --> 38:33.838
It's mentioned in the article that the library has 15 million mainly photographs, about 12 or 13 million photographs of the 15 million items in our Princeton Photographs Division.

38:33.878 --> 38:35.680
And they're public domain items, we must stress.

38:35.840 --> 38:37.662
Well, only some of them, actually.

38:37.762 --> 38:38.522
They're both.

38:39.023 --> 38:46.810
Bettman actually got a number of things from that collection himself, just had copies made of public domain things.

38:47.110 --> 39:01.492
was interested in an arrangement which never fully satisfied us, because it would have made the digital versions of these photographs too proprietary for our purposes.

39:02.153 --> 39:09.625
We view ourselves as in the business of trying to make as much available freely to the whole world as possible.

39:09.875 --> 39:15.262
And there were certain constraints on the contract they wanted to do with us, which caused us some problems.

39:15.282 --> 39:20.629
So in the end, they did, in effect, what Bettman and many others have done, which is simply to make copies of things.

39:20.729 --> 39:24.013
And then what they do with those copies is their business.

39:24.233 --> 39:26.737
Yeah, he provides immediate access.

39:27.097 --> 39:27.938
Yeah, the value added.

39:27.958 --> 39:29.340
